The person here addressed omitted to add his surname (cf. ll. 19-20) in writing to Erasmus3 and in consequence he has hitherto, so far as Î™ know, eluded identification. The title decimarius shows that he was one of the superintendents appointed by the dukes of Saxony to control the silver minesÍ¾ cf. the Ber-mannus (1. 1211), p. 131. It is therefore reasonable to suppose that he was a certain Matthias Meyner of Chemnitz, superintendent of the mines at Schneeberg, to whom on 5 Nov. 1522 Mosellanus dedicated an edition of Prudentius' Cathemerinaâ€š Leipzig, N. Faber, s.a. (see ÎŸ. Gr. Schmidt's Mosellamus, 1867, p. 72)Í¾ and who was a friend of Eppendorff (N. Arch. s. sdchs. Gesch. xxiii, 1902, p. 142). He was in office in 1515, but by 1523 his successor had been appointed. It does not follow, however, that he was dead Í¾ for the opening lines of this letter seem to indicate that he was now retiring and settling in one of the Saxon university towns, probably Leipzig, where he had matriculated in 1493, and was B.A. Sept. 1494, proceeding later M.A. His widow married Geo.
